  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, deposited in CaltechDATA by Joseph Rich and Lior Pachter, serves as the computational backbone for research examining how software package selection and version differences shape the outcomes of single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) analyses. With 35 citations recorded against its associated preprint and evidence of 36 downstream reuse events, the resource has established a clear role as a reference artifact within the reproducibility-focused corner of computational genomics.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset accompanies a scholarly investigation into a methodologically consequential question: to what extent do choices of R packages and their specific versions alter the biological conclusions drawn from scRNA-seq experiments? This concern sits at the intersection of bioinformatics, software engineering, and reproducibility science, and the underlying research addresses it empirically by providing structured data that enables systematic comparison across analytical pipelines. The resource is formally linked as a supplement to its associated preprint, and the two together constitute an integrated research output.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Academic uptake has been meaningful for a dataset of this type. The 35 citations attributable to the associated preprint indicate that researchers working in computational biology have engaged with the work as a citable source, rather than treating it as invisible infrastructure. The inferred role of \"dataset reference backbone\" reflects this pattern: the data is being drawn upon to ground or contextualize related analyses, a function that is especially valuable in a field where benchmark resources are scarce and methodological transparency is increasingly demanded by journals and funders alike.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Beyond citation counts, the reuse graph signals 36 distinct downstream reuse events, suggesting the dataset is being actively incorporated into other research workflows rather than simply acknowledged in passing. This distinction matters: passive citation and active reuse represent different levels of practical utility, and the latter implies that the data structures and outputs provided here are sufficiently well-documented and formatted to be operationalized by independent research teams. The dataset is openly accessible via CaltechDATA, a DOI-issuing institutional repository, which lowers the friction for such reuse considerably.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">One notable asymmetry in the available evidence is the absence of recorded views or downloads in the DataCite usage logs, alongside zero online event mentions at time of assessment. This likely reflects measurement gaps \u2014 DataCite usage statistics can lag or go untracked for certain repository configurations \u2014 rather than a genuine absence of engagement, given the citation and reuse signals present. The dataset's open access status under a green pathway ensures continued discoverability. Taken together, the evidence positions this resource as a technically focused but genuinely impactful contribution to the ongoing conversation about analytical reproducibility in single-cell transcriptomics.</p>",
